            "text_story": {
              "type": "cs-basic-text",
              "settings": {
                "content": "<p>A week later, I was helping my mom clean out my grandmother's attic when I found a box of old photos. As I flipped through them, I was struck by something: the women in these 1940s and 50s photos had absolutely beautiful skin.<\/p><p>Not just my grandmother, but all the women. Their skin looked healthy, clear, and naturally radiant—without a single modern skincare product in sight.<\/p><p>I mentioned this to my friend Emma, who's really into traditional living and ancestral health. She smiled knowingly and said, <strong>\"Have you ever heard of tallow?\"<\/strong><\/p><p>\"Tallow?\" I replied, completely confused.<\/p><p>\"Beef tallow,\" she explained. \"Our great-grandmothers used it for everything—cooking, candles, and especially skincare. It was the original moisturizer before the cosmetics industry convinced us we needed dozens of chemicals.\"<\/p><p>I was skeptical. Beef fat on my face? It sounded gross, outdated, and definitely not something that would help my sensitive skin.<\/p><p>But Emma's skin looked amazing. And she swore that switching to traditional, simple ingredients had completely transformed her chronic eczema.<\/p><p><strong>That night, I started researching, and what I found completely changed my perspective on skincare.<\/strong><\/p>"
              }
            },
            "heading_3": {
              "type": "cs-heading",
              "settings": {
                "tag": "h2",
                "heading": "The Truth About Modern Skincare That No One Talks About",
                "custom_size": true,
